canonical:
  title: 永明樓
  author: 權漢功
  language: lzh
  text: 白鷗波上踈踈雨黃犢坡南點點山有興卽來忘返轡長閑那似此偸閑
  rtl: true
  vertical: true
lzh_formatted:
  title: 永明樓
  author: 權漢功
  language: lzh
  text: 白鷗波上踈踈雨。黃犢坡南點點山。有興卽來忘返轡。長閑那似此偸閑。
korean:
  title: 영명루
  author: 권한공
  language: kor
  text: |-
    흰 갈매기 뜬 푸른 물결 위에는 부슬부슬 비 내리고
    누른 송아지 노는 언덕 남쪽에는 점점이 산이로다
    흥이 나면 곧 와서 고삐 돌리기 잊었노니
    다른 이의 늘 한가함이 어찌 〈나의〉 잠깐 틈을 탐만 하리
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_0240_010_0860&viewSync=OT
  footnotes: []
english:
  title: The Tower of Eternal Light
  author: Gwon Han-gong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    White gulls drift above the rippling waters where the rain falls soft and fine,
    A tawny calf at play on southern hills where mountains mark the line.
    When joy calls me, I come and forget to turn my horse's rein,
    How could another's constant leisure match the freedom that I gain?
  footnotes:
    - The Tower of Eternal Light (永明樓) was a famous pavilion, likely a reference to a real or imagined location of retreat and contemplation.
    - The poem uses natural imagery—gulls, water, calves, and hills—as metaphors for finding moments of escape from worldly duties.
    - The final couplet contrasts the speaker's stolen moments of leisure with the more permanent idleness of others, suggesting that true freedom lies in occasional, unexpected respite rather than endless vacancy.
